A: You're reading the bytes one by one, which is very inefficient. You should read the bytes into a byte array and then convert them to a string.
Here is an example:
byte[] buffer = new byte[1048576];
int readBytes = is.read(buffer);
String str = new String(buffer, 0, readBytes, "UTF-8");

This will read all the bytes from the input stream into the buffer, then convert the buffer to a string using UTF-8 encoding.
Also, you should check the return value of is.read() to make sure it's not -1 before you use the readBytes variable.

A: You can use DataInputStream to read the length of the string first, then read the string itself.
Here is an example:
DataInputStream dis = new DataInputStream(client.getInputStream());
int len = dis.readInt();
byte[] buffer = new byte[len];
dis.readFully(buffer);
String str = new String(buffer, "UTF-8");

On the server side, you can send the length of the string first, then send the string itself.
Here is an example:
String str = "Your string here";
byte[] buffer = str.getBytes("UTF-8");
DataOutputStream dos = new DataOutputStream(client.getOutputStream());
dos.writeInt(buffer.length);
dos.write(buffer);

This way, you can read and write strings in a more efficient way.

